Intro to Windows forensics

Windows dominates the Desktop & laptop market by 87%, which means that most of the investigations you will come across involve performing forensic analysis on a Windows machine.

 

Windows Market Share

 

Windows is a complex operating system with tons of forensic artifacts. Each artifact provides a specific piece of information, and you, as a forensic analyst, are expected to know where to look for answers during investigations. Otherwise, you risk losing valuable time!

The simple way to look at Windows artifacts is by breaking them down into machine-related and user-related information, the same way the Windows registry categorizes them  (HKEY_LOCAL_MACHINE and HKEY_CURRENT_USER).  The first are artifacts relevant to the computer regardless of the user (e.g., IP address, hostname..etc.), while the latter contains information specific to each user (e.g., username, password, file actions...etc.).

 

 

One thing to note is that during investigations, there are multiple ways to find a specific piece of information. For example, you can find Windows installation date and time in both the registry and event logs. There is no standard way to perform Windows forensics, and each analyst can take a different route. The important thing, though, is your ability to ask the right question and find answers.

 

There are multiple versions of the Windows operating system, such as Windows 7, 8, and 10, but they all share a common list of artifacts. In this module, we will focus on Windows 10, being the most popular version running in enterprises right now.
 

You may be wondering, what about other versions? Do not worry! The knowledge you will gain through this module will allow you to perform investigations successfully on different windows versions. As we keep saying, security is a mindset. Once you develop the right one, you can tackle any challenge.
